WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.390 --> 00:00:06.790
In July 2020, Singapore held its 13th General
Election — the purpose of which is to elect

00:00:06.790 --> 00:00:09.060
the country’s parliament.

00:00:09.060 --> 00:00:15.330
At stake, however, was not really the ruling
party, its policies, or even the general direction

00:00:15.330 --> 00:00:17.160
of the nation.

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:22.550
Those were already known to anyone with half
a brain: The People’s Action Party would

00:00:22.550 --> 00:00:27.840
retain power, as it has for nearly six consecutive
decades.

00:00:27.840 --> 00:00:33.620
Also nearly certain was that it would win
somewhere between 60 and 70% of the vote — a

00:00:33.620 --> 00:00:39.100
range it has deviated from only once in the
previous 36 years.

00:00:39.100 --> 00:00:44.210
You might assume, given its predictability,
that the election was somehow fraudulent.

00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:47.050
But, you’d be wrong.

00:00:47.050 --> 00:00:52.670
Unlike its Southeast Asian neighbors Laos
and Vietnam, elections in Singapore are free

00:00:52.670 --> 00:00:55.800
from intimidation or tampering.

00:00:55.800 --> 00:01:00.969
Knowing this, you might instead conclude that
the election simply didn’t matter.

00:01:00.969 --> 00:01:03.640
Again, you’d be wrong.

00:01:03.640 --> 00:01:09.470
If 70% voted for the People’s Action Party,
the exercise would be deemed a great success,

00:01:09.470 --> 00:01:12.880
cementing the party’s medium-term future.

00:01:12.880 --> 00:01:18.840
Win 60%, instead, its worst showing in the
country’s history, and it would be a humiliating

00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:23.090
failure, giving rise to speculation about
its future.

00:01:23.090 --> 00:01:29.100
In either case, it would win by a margin unheard
of in most free democracies.

00:01:29.100 --> 00:01:36.020
The true number was 61.24%, a moderate disappointment
for the ruling party, and one that will have

00:01:36.020 --> 00:01:39.930
some tangible impact on the next five years.

00:01:39.930 --> 00:01:44.689
And yet, no one seriously contemplated any
other outcome.

00:01:44.689 --> 00:01:49.340
Even opposition parties don’t profess the
ability to dethrone the PAP — a claim that

00:01:49.340 --> 00:01:53.590
would be so far-fetched as to destroy all
credibility.

00:01:53.590 --> 00:02:00.060
Such is the strange state of politics on the
very strange island known as Singapore.

00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:06.539
Its very existence continues to baffle outsiders,
who struggle to place it on any spectrum.

00:02:06.539 --> 00:02:10.979
Because while most countries belong somewhere
in the grey area between “Democratic”

00:02:10.979 --> 00:02:17.420
and “Authoritarian”, Singapore is an exceptionally
rare blend — one described both as “a

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:23.130
technocratic dream state”, and a “thinly
veiled dictatorship” simultaneously by those

00:02:23.130 --> 00:02:25.030
more or less sympathetic.

00:02:25.030 --> 00:02:28.070
So, what is it?

00:02:28.070 --> 00:02:33.330
The answer reveals just as much about this
tiny red dot off the Malay Peninsula as it

00:02:33.330 --> 00:02:39.920
does about your true feelings towards democracy
and the very purpose of government.

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:41.640
Sponsored by Skillshare.

00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:46.680
Get a one-month free trial and start learning
everything from photography to graphic design

00:02:46.680 --> 00:02:49.290
from yours truly.

00:02:49.290 --> 00:02:53.819
As colonies around the world gained their
independence in the mid 20th century, many

00:02:53.819 --> 00:02:58.790
reacted by aggressively rejecting Western
investment, seeing it as a continuation of

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:00.640
imperial exploitation.

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:07.629
In 1959, for example, Indonesia went so far
as to legally bar foreigners from doing business

00:03:07.629 --> 00:03:13.030
in the countryside, forcing them to transfer
ownership to an Indonesian national.

00:03:13.030 --> 00:03:19.680
Singapore, on the other hand, was in a strange
position: It had no natural resources.

00:03:19.680 --> 00:03:26.239
With no diamonds, oil, or timber to exploit,
Singapore had no invader to fight.

00:03:26.239 --> 00:03:31.060
The British were no saints, that’s for sure,
but they did not leave Singapore with the

00:03:31.060 --> 00:03:34.510
same bad taste in its mouth as other colonies.

00:03:34.510 --> 00:03:39.799
Un-toppled statues and English street names
still litter the island.

00:03:39.799 --> 00:03:43.360
Foreign investment was, in fact, its only
option.

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:49.970
And so it set out to design the country Philips,
Shell, and Canon had previously only dreamed

00:03:49.970 --> 00:03:50.970
of.

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:55.900
There would be no taxes, no protests, no corruption,
and no change of leadership.

00:03:55.900 --> 00:04:01.129
A country run like a corporation, for corporations.

00:04:01.129 --> 00:04:06.180
After the People’s Action Party was democratically
elected, it wasted no time obliterating any

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:11.020
and all forms of “instability” — whether
they be socialist rivals, labor unions, or

00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:12.939
student activists.

00:04:12.939 --> 00:04:17.830
The party unapologetically arrested or disappeared
them all.

00:04:17.830 --> 00:04:23.250
But in its desire to please multinational
mega-corporations, Singapore also implemented

00:04:23.250 --> 00:04:27.320
what are known today as some of the best things
about the country.

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:32.640
Its world-class public education system was
designed to churn out highly educated, obedient

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:37.970
workers by “streaming” children into accelerated,
vocational, or “normal” tracks, with no

00:04:37.970 --> 00:04:40.470
pretense of equality.

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:46.580
Its unrivaled healthcare system ensured citizens
and wealthy expat bankers alike stayed happy

00:04:46.580 --> 00:04:50.000
and healthy — thus, productive.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.010
Its enviable public housing helped integrate
its three main ethnic groups — Chinese,

00:04:55.010 --> 00:04:58.780
Malay, and Indians — by making them neighbors.

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:02.100
Race riots are, after all, bad for business.

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:07.320
The secret to Singapore’s clean streets,
timely public transit, and well-respected

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:14.190
institutions is simple: When you have 6 decades
of uninterrupted power, zero accountability,

00:05:14.190 --> 00:05:19.410
and no opposition to slow things down, you
truly can just get things done.

00:05:19.410 --> 00:05:25.560
Singapore’s anti-democratic tendencies are
neither unusual in the world, nor especially

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:28.180
egregious in comparison.

00:05:28.180 --> 00:05:32.590
Their purpose, however, was to support rapid
economic growth.

00:05:32.590 --> 00:05:36.620
Whether economic growth was ultimately in
service of raising the standard of living

00:05:36.620 --> 00:05:41.050
or retaining the party’s grip on power is
disputed.

00:05:41.050 --> 00:05:47.100
What cannot be disputed is that it has now
achieved that all-important economic growth.

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:52.770
With the same GDP per capita as the U.S.,
Denmark, and Qatar, Singapore is now one of

00:05:52.770 --> 00:05:58.290
the richest, most prosperous, and comfortable
places to live on planet Earth.

00:05:58.290 --> 00:06:02.070
And yet the PAP has resisted democracy.

00:06:02.070 --> 00:06:06.990
Singapore has been called a “thin”, “procedural”,
“hollow”, “proxy”, or “bureaucratic”

00:06:06.990 --> 00:06:12.530
democracy, as well as a “competitive authoritarian
state” because its elections are completely

00:06:12.530 --> 00:06:15.590
free, but not the least bit fair.

00:06:15.590 --> 00:06:21.060
In addition to normal incumbent advantages
— passing popular policies immediately before

00:06:21.060 --> 00:06:25.830
an election and being able to call one at
the most convenient time — it also employs

00:06:25.830 --> 00:06:29.280
a wide range of tools to disadvantage the
opposition.

00:06:29.280 --> 00:06:35.270
For starters, preparation can begin only after
an election is called.

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:38.970
Even then, politicians can’t actually campaign.

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:45.000
Since 1968, the legal “campaign period”
has lasted no more than 11 days — giving

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:49.190
the opposition less than two weeks to present
their case to voters.

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:54.770
In other words, Singaporeans have only been
exposed to the alternative 109 days in the

00:06:54.770 --> 00:06:57.250
past half-century.

00:06:57.250 --> 00:06:59.220
It gets far worse.

00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:04.020
The Prime FMinister has the unchecked right
to draw the electoral boundaries — leading

00:07:04.020 --> 00:07:06.040
to intense gerrymandering.

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:13.940
In 2020, some districts had just 19,000 voters
while others had nearly twice that number.

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:18.740
One neighborhood has suspiciously been moved
between four different districts from 1988

00:07:18.740 --> 00:07:19.740
to 2011.

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:26.160
And in 2020, the PAP dissolved three districts
from the 2015 election — see if you can

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:28.340
find what they had in common.

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:30.000
That’s not all!

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:35.430
The Prime Minister can redraw boundaries whenever
he or she wishes — meaning the opposition

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:40.240
may not even know which constituency they’re
contesting until the last minute.

00:07:40.240 --> 00:07:45.990
In 2001, districts were announced one day
before the election was called, which took

00:07:45.990 --> 00:07:48.730
place 16 days later.

00:07:48.730 --> 00:07:53.140
When all those things aren’t enough, the
“men in white” resort to good ‘ole fashioned

00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:54.140
lawsuits.

00:07:54.140 --> 00:08:01.790
A long list of opposition politicians, writers,
and activists have been sued for defamation.

00:08:01.790 --> 00:08:07.000
One blogger was ordered to pay the Prime Minister
$100,000 US dollars in damages for sharing

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.500
a link to an article on Facebook without comment.

00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:12.740
No one is above the law.

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:18.150
The New York Times, Wall Street Journal, Bloomberg,
and The Economist have all been targeted — which

00:08:18.150 --> 00:08:22.830
helps explain why you might know the country
as an efficiently-run resort rather than an

00:08:22.830 --> 00:08:24.960
authoritarian regime.

00:08:24.960 --> 00:08:30.710
Finally, it grants token positions to opposition
parties, requires some districts to be elected

00:08:30.710 --> 00:08:35.870
in groups, which favors large parties, and
has in the past used its broadly-defined Sedition

00:08:35.870 --> 00:08:37.760
Act to arrest dissidents.

00:08:37.760 --> 00:08:44.290
To summarize: the ruling party decides when,
where, and how elections take place.

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:48.110
It can arrest or bankrupt anyone it wishes.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:51.440
To be clear, the party is not free from consequences.

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:57.550
A very prominent Minister of Foreign Affairs
lost his race in 2011, for instance.

00:08:57.550 --> 00:09:02.060
But it works very hard to ensure that never
happens.

00:09:02.060 --> 00:09:07.580
You may wonder why Singaporeans accept its
lack of democratic accountability.

00:09:07.580 --> 00:09:13.200
But a better question might be: Can they consent
to the PAP’s rule while being so insulated

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:15.470
from the alternatives?

00:09:15.470 --> 00:09:20.090
Protests are illegal unless pre-approved by
the government, and its colonial-era laws

00:09:20.090 --> 00:09:22.620
have been used to silence critics.

00:09:22.620 --> 00:09:27.020
In 2017, a silent protest was held on public
transit.

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:31.560
The activists were charged with vandalism
— a crime punishable with up to three years

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:38.390
in prison and 8 strokes of the cane — for,
get this, taping a piece of paper to the wall.

00:09:38.390 --> 00:09:43.090
More recently, a man was charged for participating
in an “illegal assembly” for holding a

00:09:43.090 --> 00:09:45.830
piece of cardboard with a smiley face in public.

00:09:45.830 --> 00:09:47.990
He was alone.

00:09:47.990 --> 00:09:51.180
Censorship extends to the media, as well.

00:09:51.180 --> 00:09:57.350
The government has the power to install any
director or editor of its choice to any newspaper.

00:09:57.350 --> 00:10:02.570
It can also simply revoke the media license
of anyone not sufficiently cooperative.

00:10:02.570 --> 00:10:07.170
All traditional outlets, including The Straits
Times, are therefore government mouthpieces.

00:10:07.170 --> 00:10:12.600
And while the internet initially gave the
opposition a new avenue to reach voters, the

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:15.830
PAP recently began taking on Facebook, too.

00:10:15.830 --> 00:10:21.270
The “Protection from Online Falsehoods and
Manipulation” — aka “Fake news” — Bill,

00:10:21.270 --> 00:10:26.000
gives the same ministers up for election the
ability to force their opponents to “correct”

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:29.570
or remove their statements online or risk
jail.

00:10:29.570 --> 00:10:34.220
In essence, the PAP granted itself the right
to silence the opposition.

00:10:34.220 --> 00:10:39.280
And because they’re silenced, the opposition
will never have the opportunity to challenge...

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:41.030
that very law.

00:10:41.030 --> 00:10:46.500
The PAP’s 60% share of votes seems much
less decisive when you realize the extreme

00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:49.920
lengths it goes to disadvantage its opponents.

00:10:49.920 --> 00:10:55.840
If 2/5ths of the country still voted for another
party after all that, perhaps it doesn’t

00:10:55.840 --> 00:10:58.120
have such strong consent.

00:10:58.120 --> 00:11:01.790
Then again, perhaps it does.

00:11:01.790 --> 00:11:06.150
Another theory says that Singaporeans are
making an informed decision — that they

00:11:06.150 --> 00:11:09.120
know exactly the trade-off they’re making.

00:11:09.120 --> 00:11:15.190
In one survey, 64% of respondents said they
considered economic development more important

00:11:15.190 --> 00:11:16.950
than democracy.

00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:22.840
If Singapore truly is a corporation, as Lee
Kuan Yew intended, it must pay its workers

00:11:22.840 --> 00:11:27.530
— (citizens) — a competitive wage or risk
losing them to a competitor.

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:31.230
The relationship appears transactional.

00:11:31.230 --> 00:11:36.330
Citizens want things to improve: schools to
get better, healthcare to get cheaper, and

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:37.380
so on.

00:11:37.380 --> 00:11:41.030
The party, meanwhile, seeks legitimacy.

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:44.230
Decisive electoral victories signal its “right”
to rule.

00:11:44.230 --> 00:11:49.800
And if the purpose of an election is merely
to measure support, having an opposition doesn’t

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:51.080
much matter.

00:11:51.080 --> 00:11:57.210
In the eyes of the party, only one number
is relevant: the share of votes it receives.

00:11:57.210 --> 00:12:01.980
The current Prime Minister revealed his true
views on democracy when he criticized voters

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:05.960
who supported the opposition as “free-riders”.

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:10.560
In his view, not voting for the PAP is akin
to not showing up for work while expecting

00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:12.330
a paycheck.

00:12:12.330 --> 00:12:18.290
This was made explicit in 2015, when the government
announced it would give priority to PAP voters

00:12:18.290 --> 00:12:20.960
when doing public housing maintenance.

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:26.680
Frustrated by opposition voters, the party
finally gave up the veneer of fairness.

00:12:26.680 --> 00:12:30.950
Perhaps because it thought voters were too
stupid to pick up on its hints, it finally

00:12:30.950 --> 00:12:36.000
spelled out the trade in plain English: Vote
for us and we’ll fix your elevators and

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:37.470
pipes sooner.

00:12:37.470 --> 00:12:44.600
82% of Singaporeans in one survey said they’re
“satisfied with the way democracy works”

00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:49.740
in the country, yet 61% voted for the PAP
last year.

00:12:49.740 --> 00:12:54.470
One way to interpret these numbers is that
voters are, by and large, content with the

00:12:54.470 --> 00:12:58.900
deal they have with the PAP, but wish to send
a message.

00:12:58.900 --> 00:13:02.540
They don’t want a change of leadership,
but they also don’t want to write a blank

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:03.990
check.

00:13:03.990 --> 00:13:07.790
Realizing that the outcome of the election
is virtually guaranteed — they can instead

00:13:07.790 --> 00:13:11.240
treat their vote as a form of polite protest.

00:13:11.240 --> 00:13:16.600
The PAP, somewhat hilariously, calls this
“irrational voter behavior”, but in truth,

00:13:16.600 --> 00:13:19.270
they have no one to blame but themselves.

00:13:19.270 --> 00:13:23.670
By turning elections into nothing more than
an opinion poll, they’ve allowed Singaporeans

00:13:23.670 --> 00:13:27.920
the ability to remind the government of their
leverage without facing consequences.

00:13:27.920 --> 00:13:34.920
They can vote based not on who they want in
power, but what message they wish to send.

00:13:34.920 --> 00:13:39.650
With its share of votes trending downwards
over time, the People’s Action Party faces

00:13:39.650 --> 00:13:44.180
a dilemma:
As the odds of what it calls a “freak election”

00:13:44.180 --> 00:13:49.360
appear less and less farfetched, it has two
options to remain in power.

00:13:49.360 --> 00:13:52.430
The first is that it could continue weakening
the opposition.

00:13:52.430 --> 00:13:58.110
Increasingly, this has meant blurring the
line between the party and the country itself.

00:13:58.110 --> 00:14:04.650
The Lee family dynasty — father and son
— has ruled Singapore for 48 of 62 years,

00:14:04.650 --> 00:14:07.730
or 77% of its existence.

00:14:07.730 --> 00:14:12.770
The number of buildings, awards, and schools
named in their honor would make Kim Il-Sung

00:14:12.770 --> 00:14:14.190
jealous.

00:14:14.190 --> 00:14:19.839
It also manufactures crises, perpetuating
the “survivalist” mentality — that Singapore

00:14:19.839 --> 00:14:24.360
is a “new” or “fragile” nation and
therefore needs strong, experienced leaders

00:14:24.360 --> 00:14:26.180
at the helm.

00:14:26.180 --> 00:14:31.901
Somehow every one of the last 60 years has
been so tumultuous as to require “just another

00:14:31.901 --> 00:14:34.860
few years” of repression.

00:14:34.860 --> 00:14:41.960
The second way the PAP could stay in power
is, ironically, to do the opposite: democratize.

00:14:41.960 --> 00:14:47.270
Counterintuitive as it may sound, it's clear
that most voters like the PAP and have doubts

00:14:47.270 --> 00:14:49.200
about the alternatives.

00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:54.780
But because the opposition is so heavily disadvantaged,
voters may “grade them on a curve”, giving

00:14:54.780 --> 00:14:57.870
them more credit than perhaps they deserve.

00:14:57.870 --> 00:15:02.980
If elections were fair, citizens would likely
vote fairly as well.

00:15:02.980 --> 00:15:06.910
Introducing some democratic reforms may also
win respect.

00:15:06.910 --> 00:15:12.000
“Delivering economic growth” is a fairly
weak source of legitimacy.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.630
With an economy closely connected to the world’s,
it could easily fail to deliver through no

00:15:16.630 --> 00:15:18.560
fault of its own.

00:15:18.560 --> 00:15:23.180
If it were to do the “right” thing instead
and impose limits on itself, its support would

00:15:23.180 --> 00:15:25.320
be much more durable.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:32.470
By treating them more generously, Singapore
Incorporated might have more loyal workers.

00:15:32.470 --> 00:15:35.330
What does it really matter, you may ask.

00:15:35.330 --> 00:15:40.630
If the PAP democratizes but stays in power,
the end result is the same.

00:15:40.630 --> 00:15:45.430
But such an argument neglects one of the biggest
benefits of democracy…

00:15:45.430 --> 00:15:50.590
When people hear about Singapore, they often
experience the same pattern of grief.

00:15:50.590 --> 00:15:56.470
Unable or unwilling to believe housing, healthcare,
or education are simple, “solvable” problems,

00:15:56.470 --> 00:15:59.430
they find reasons why Singapore is different.

00:15:59.430 --> 00:16:03.350
“That’s great”, they say, “but it
only works because it’s — fill in the

00:16:03.350 --> 00:16:08.050
blank — small, cosmopolitan, Confucian,
etc.”

00:16:08.050 --> 00:16:12.720
When they learn the only thing stopping these
policies from being exported elsewhere is

00:16:12.720 --> 00:16:16.690
politics, they move on, looking for other
reasons to dismiss it.

00:16:16.690 --> 00:16:22.089
Usually, this means pointing out that Singapore
still practices caning — true — or bans

00:16:22.089 --> 00:16:26.740
chewing gum — true, but don’t forget New
York banned soda.

00:16:26.740 --> 00:16:32.260
By focusing on the comical and outlandish
— the chewing gum ban, or astronomical fines

00:16:32.260 --> 00:16:36.790
for littering — they miss the real problem
with Singapore.

00:16:36.790 --> 00:16:41.610
Lack of accountability allowed the People’s
Action Party to implement effective, efficient,

00:16:41.610 --> 00:16:43.250
enviable policies.

00:16:43.250 --> 00:16:46.310
But it also came at an invisible cost.

00:16:46.310 --> 00:16:51.670
By taking the authoritarian shortcut, Singapore
took a massive gamble.

00:16:51.670 --> 00:16:57.040
One that happened to pay off — but one that
could also crumble at any moment.

00:16:57.040 --> 00:17:02.250
If a less benevolent party or politician were
to win power, there’s no telling what kind

00:17:02.250 --> 00:17:06.079
of permanent, lethal damage it could do to
the country.

00:17:06.079 --> 00:17:11.340
And thanks to the PAP, there would be no easy
way to vote it out of power.

00:17:11.340 --> 00:17:16.670
History has taught us to expect the People’s
Action Party will take the former path — devolving

00:17:16.670 --> 00:17:21.970
into nationalism and crushing the opposition
until nothing is left.

00:17:21.970 --> 00:17:25.050
But Singapore is no ordinary country.

00:17:25.050 --> 00:17:30.580
We should all hope it’s not ordinary in
this respect, either.

